questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following connections generally use series connections?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Household appliances&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. Small bulb-decorations on Deepawali&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct code.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Concept&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Resistance:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;obstruction offered&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;flow of current&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is known as the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;resistance&lt;/span&gt;. It is denoted by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;R.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Series Connection:&lt;/strong&gt; When&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;two or more resistances&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are connected&amp;nbsp;one after another such that the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;same current flows through them&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;then it is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;resistances in series&lt;/span&gt;. The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;equivalent resistance&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in series combination is will be&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;R&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;ser&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;= R&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;+ R&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;+ R&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/03/F1_Jitendra_Deepak_30.03.2020_D7.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 234px; height: 86px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Current in each resistor remains same in series connection&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Voltage is dropped in each resistor&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Generally used in small bulb decorations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parallel Connection:&lt;/strong&gt; When the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;terminals of two or more resistances&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are connected at the same two points and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;the potential difference across them is equal&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;then it is called&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;resistances in parallel.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;net resistance/equivalent resistance(R)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of resistances in parallel is given by:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/03/F1_Jitendra_Deepak_30.03.2020_D8.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 316px; height: 133px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{R} = \frac{1}{{{R_1}}} + \frac{1}{{{R_2}}}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Voltage remains same in each resistor&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Current divides at each&amp;nbsp;the junction&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Generally used in house hold appliances because each appliance works only on&amp;nbsp;rated voltage (generally 220 V).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Consider the following statements regarding Ohm&amp;#39;s law:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S1: &lt;/strong&gt;According to Ohm&amp;#39;s law, the resistance of a conductor is inversely proportional to the voltage across it, provided the temperature remains constant.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S2:&lt;/strong&gt; Ohm&amp;#39;s law states that the current flowing through a conductor is inversely proportional to the resistance of the conductor, given a constant voltage.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Which statement is correct?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Only S2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law is a fundamental principle in electronics and electrical engineering that describes the relationship between voltage (V), current (I), and resistance (R) in an electrical circuit. It is named after the German physicist Georg Simon Ohm, who first formulated this law in 1827.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law states that the current flowing through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the voltage across the two points.&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​V = I&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; R&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;V = Voltage&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;I= Current&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;R= Resistance&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law applies to various electrical components and circuits, including resistors, conductors, and simple circuits composed of resistive elements. It provides a fundamental framework for analyzing and designing electrical systems.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;According to Ohm&amp;#39;s law, the resistance of a conductor is directly proportional to the voltage across it, provided the temperature remains constant.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s law states that the current flowing through a conductor is inversely proportional to the resistance of the conductor, given a constant voltage.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Ohm&#039;s Law: Learn Definition, Formula, Verification, Uses &amp;amp; FAQ&#039;s&quot; src=&quot;https://blogmedia.testbook.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/ohms-law_2-85cc000e.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, statement 2 is correct&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(32, 33, 36);&quot;&gt;states that&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the voltage across a conductor is directly proportional to the current flowing through it, provided all physical conditions and temperature, remain constant&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(32, 33, 36);&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#202124&quot;&gt;Mathematically,&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;current-voltage can be written as&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;V = IR, where V&amp;nbsp;= Voltage, I = Current, R = Resistance&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/23/01/F1_Vinanti_Teaching_24.01.23_D6.png&quot; style=&quot; width: 201px; height: 152px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From Ohm&amp;#39;s law, V = IR&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Slope,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(R=\frac{V}{I}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, V - I graph gives the value of resistance.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the slope for R&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;is maximum and the slope for R&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;nbsp;is minimum.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, R&lt;sub&gt;3&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;gt; R&lt;sub&gt;2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;gt; R&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

