&lt;p&gt;Which of the following is the &lt;em&gt;correct&lt;/em&gt; deduction?&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;CONCEPT&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Ohm&amp;rsquo;s law&lt;/span&gt;: The Current through the metallic element is directly proportional to the potential difference when the temperature remains constant. i.e.,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I &amp;prop; V or V &amp;prop; I or V = IR&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where V = potential difference, I = current, and R = resistance&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ohm&amp;rsquo;s law is not a universal law, the substances, which&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;obey ohm&amp;rsquo;s law&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are known&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;as ohmic substance. e.g. aluminium, copper, silver conductors, etc.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The substance which&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;does not obey ohm&amp;rsquo;s law&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;non-ohmic substance&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;e.g. gases, crystal rectifiers, thermionic valves,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;transistors, semiconductors&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;diode&lt;/span&gt;, bulb filaments, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_12.6.20_Pallavi_D1.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 356px; height: 185px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;If the graph between current (I) and Voltage (V) is a straight line, they obey ohm&amp;rsquo;s law.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The non- ohmic resistors show a curve in the graph.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;EXPLANATION&lt;/u&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;When the &lt;strong&gt;temperature of the metal conductor is raised&lt;/strong&gt;, the number density (n) of electrons in the metal conductor does not change appreciably.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;However, the&lt;strong&gt; ions/atoms of the metal vibrate with greater amplitudes about their mean positions&lt;/strong&gt; (i.e. lattice sites).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Due to an increase in thermal energy, the frequency of collision of free electrons with atoms/ions while drifting towards the positive end of the conductor also increases.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;This &lt;strong&gt;reduces the average relaxation time (&amp;tau;)&lt;/strong&gt;. Hence, the &lt;strong&gt;value of electrical resistance R increases&lt;/strong&gt; with &lt;strong&gt;rise of temperature&lt;/strong&gt;. Therefore option 2 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

